<section id="what-is">
      <h2>What Is the Spring Festival?</h2>
      <p>The Spring Festival (<span class="chinese-char">春節</span>, <span class="pinyin">Chūnjié</span>), also known as Chinese New Year, marks the beginning of a new year on the traditional <a href="/calendar/">Chinese lunisolar calendar</a>. It is the most important festival in Chinese culture, celebrated for at least 3,500 years, and the longest public holiday in China and many East Asian nations.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="naming-history">
      <h2>The Name "Spring Festival" (<span class="chinese-char">春節</span>)</h2>
      <div class="historical-note">
        <p>The name "Spring Festival" is surprisingly recent. For over a thousand years, the lunar new year was called <strong><span class="chinese-char">元旦</span></strong> (<span class="pinyin">Yuándàn</span>, "first morning"). The earliest documented use appears in a poem by Xiao Ziyun (<span class="chinese-char">蕭子雲</span>) of the Liang Dynasty (502–557 CE): <em>"四氣新元旦，萬壽初今朝"</em> ("The four seasons begin anew at Yuandan, ten thousand years of longevity start this morning").</p>
      </div>
      <p>The name change came through two political acts in rapid succession:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>1912</strong> — Sun Yat-sen (<span class="chinese-char">孫中山</span>) proclaimed the Republic of China and adopted the Gregorian calendar. He reassigned the name <span class="chinese-char">元旦</span> (Yuándàn) to January 1st on the Gregorian calendar, leaving the lunar new year temporarily unnamed.</li>
        <li><strong>January 23, 1914</strong> — Yuan Shikai's Interior Minister Zhu Qiqian (<span class="chinese-char">朱啟鈐</span>) formally proposed renaming the lunar new year as <span class="chinese-char">春節</span> (Chūnjié, "Spring Festival"). The proposal was approved, giving the celebration its modern name.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>In 1949, the People's Republic of China reconfirmed this arrangement. The term <span class="chinese-char">春節</span> is thus a 20th-century political creation — the celebration itself is ancient, but its current name dates only to 1914.</p>
      <div class="source-box">
        <p>Before 1914, the lunar new year was variously called <span class="chinese-char">元旦</span> (Yuándàn), <span class="chinese-char">歲首</span> (Suìshǒu, "year's head"), <span class="chinese-char">正旦</span> (Zhèngdàn, "first dawn"), or simply <span class="chinese-char">過年</span> (Guònián, "passing the year") — a colloquial term still universally used today.</p>
        <cite>— Historical note on pre-Republican naming conventions</cite>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="origins">
      <h2>Ancient Origins</h2>
      <p>The festival's roots lie in ancient year-end sacrificial rites (<span class="chinese-char">臘祭</span>, làjì) during the Shang Dynasty, when people offered sacrifices to ancestors and deities to give thanks for the harvest and pray for a prosperous new year. The word "Nian" (<span class="chinese-char">年</span>) originally referred to the ripening of grain &mdash; a full harvest cycle.</p>
      <p>By the Zhou Dynasty, formalised celebrations at year's end included communal feasting and ritual offerings. Emperor Wu of Han's calendar reform in 104 BCE fixed the new year to the first day of the first lunar month, establishing the date that has endured for over two thousand years.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="nian-legend">
      <h2>The Nian Beast Myth — A Modern Invention</h2>
      <div class="historical-note">
        <p><strong>Scholarly correction:</strong> The "Nian beast" (<span class="chinese-char">年獸</span>, <span class="pinyin">Niánshòu</span>) story, widely presented as an ancient Chinese legend, is in fact a <strong>20th-century invention</strong>. No pre-Qing source mentions a beast called "Nian."</p>
      </div>
      <p>The earliest known appearance of the Nian beast story is in a piece by <strong>Sun Yusheng</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">孫玉聲</span>) published in the Shanghai tabloid <em>《金剛鑽》</em> on <strong>January 17, 1933</strong>. Sun's version described a monster that feared red, loud noises, and fire — neatly "explaining" existing customs. The story was then amplified by a <strong>1980 <em>《人民日報》</em></strong> (People's Daily) article, which created the canonical version that subsequently entered school textbooks across China and abroad.</p>
      <p>The character <span class="chinese-char">年</span> (<span class="pinyin">nián</span>) itself has nothing to do with a beast. The Eastern Han dictionary <em>《說文解字》</em> (<span class="pinyin">Shuōwén Jiězì</span>, c. 100 CE) by Xu Shen defines it clearly: <strong>"年，穀熟也"</strong> — "Nian means the ripening of grain." The word referred to the annual agricultural harvest cycle, not a creature.</p>
      <div class="pullquote">
        The Nian beast story is creative modern folklore — but it should not be mistaken for authentic ancient tradition. The real origins of Spring Festival customs are more interesting, better documented, and far older.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="authentic-customs">
      <h2>Authentic Pre-Qing Origins of New Year Customs</h2>
      <p>The Spring Festival customs falsely attributed to the Nian beast each have their own distinct, well-documented histories:</p>

      <h3>Firecrackers (<span class="chinese-char">爆竹</span>, <span class="pinyin">Bàozhú</span>)</h3>
      <div class="source-box">
        <p>"正月一日……雞鳴而起，先於庭前爆竹，以辟山臊惡鬼。"</p>
        <p>"On the first day of the first month… rise at cockcrow, and set off bamboo crackers in the courtyard to drive away the mountain sprites and evil ghosts (<span class="chinese-char">山臊</span>/<span class="chinese-char">山魈</span>)."</p>
        <cite>— Zong Lin (<span class="chinese-char">宗懍</span>), <em>《荊楚歲時記》</em> (Record of the Seasons of Jing and Chu), 6th century CE</cite>
      </div>
      <p>The original "firecrackers" were literally <strong>exploding bamboo</strong> — green bamboo stalks thrown into fires, which burst loudly as trapped air expanded. The practice targeted <span class="chinese-char">山臊</span> (<span class="pinyin">shānsāo</span>) or <span class="chinese-char">山魈</span> (<span class="pinyin">shānxiāo</span>), mountain spirits believed to cause illness — not any beast called "Nian." Gunpowder firecrackers appeared after the Tang Dynasty invention of black powder, eventually replacing bamboo.</p>

      <h3>Red Decorations — from Peachwood Charms (<span class="chinese-char">桃符</span>, <span class="pinyin">Táofú</span>)</h3>
      <p>Red decorations did not originate from a beast's fear. They evolved from <strong><span class="chinese-char">桃符</span></strong> (táofú) — peachwood boards inscribed with the names of protective deities <strong><span class="chinese-char">神荼</span></strong> (<span class="pinyin">Shéntú</span>) and <strong><span class="chinese-char">鬱壘</span></strong> (<span class="pinyin">Yùlěi</span>), hung beside doors to repel evil. This practice is documented from the Han Dynasty. During the Five Dynasties (907–960 CE), auspicious couplets began replacing deity names. By the <strong>Ming Dynasty</strong>, peachwood was replaced by <strong>red paper</strong>, completing the evolution to the spring couplets (<span class="chinese-char">春聯</span>) we recognise today.</p>

      <h3>Door Gods (<span class="chinese-char">門神</span>, <span class="pinyin">Ménshén</span>)</h3>
      <p>Door gods evolved through three stages:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Han Dynasty</strong> — <span class="chinese-char">桃符</span> boards with the names Shentu and Yulei carved on them</li>
        <li><strong>Sui–Tang period</strong> — Carved wooden deity figures replaced inscriptions</li>
        <li><strong>Tang Dynasty onward</strong> — Painted generals <strong>Qin Shubao</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">秦叔寶</span>) and <strong>Yuchi Gong</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">尉遲恭</span>) became the dominant door god pair, based on a legend about Emperor Taizong's nightmares</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Spring Couplets (<span class="chinese-char">春聯</span>, <span class="pinyin">Chūnlián</span>)</h3>
      <p>The tradition of paired auspicious poetry on doorframes originated in the <strong>Five Dynasties period</strong> (907–960 CE). The earliest recorded spring couplet is attributed to Meng Chang (<span class="chinese-char">孟昶</span>), the last ruler of Later Shu: <em>"新年納餘慶，嘉節號長春"</em> ("In the new year receive lasting blessings; on this fine festival, hail enduring spring"). The practice moved from peachwood boards to red paper during the Ming Dynasty, when Emperor Taizu is said to have encouraged their widespread adoption.</p>

      <h3>Staying Up on New Year's Eve (<span class="chinese-char">守歲</span>, <span class="pinyin">Shǒusuì</span>)</h3>
      <p>The custom of staying awake through New Year's Eve is documented since the <strong>Jin Dynasty</strong> (265–420 CE). The poet Zhou Chu (<span class="chinese-char">周處</span>) described the practice in <em>《風土記》</em>: families gathered, feasted, and stayed up together to "guard the year's passing." This had nothing to do with fearing a beast — it was an act of reverence for time, family unity, and the threshold between old and new.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="fifteen-days">
      <h2>The Fifteen Days of Celebration</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>New Year's Eve (<span class="chinese-char">除夕</span>, Chúxī)</strong> &mdash; The most important night. Families gather for the reunion dinner (<span class="chinese-char">年夜飯</span>). Staying up until midnight (<span class="chinese-char">守歲</span>, shǒusuì) is practised to bid farewell to the old year.</li>
        <li><strong>Day 1</strong> &mdash; Firecrackers at dawn. Wearing new clothes. Visiting elders and receiving red envelopes (<span class="chinese-char">紅包</span>). Auspicious greetings exchanged.</li>
        <li><strong>Day 2</strong> &mdash; Married daughters return to their parents' home (<span class="chinese-char">回娘家</span>). Prayers to the God of Wealth.</li>
        <li><strong>Days 3-4</strong> &mdash; Continuing family visits. In some traditions, Day 3 is considered unlucky for visiting to avoid arguments.</li>
        <li><strong>Day 5</strong> &mdash; Welcoming the God of Wealth (<span class="chinese-char">財神</span>, Cáishén). Firecrackers to attract prosperity. Businesses traditionally reopen.</li>
        <li><strong>Days 6-14</strong> &mdash; Temple fairs (<span class="chinese-char">廟會</span>), folk performances, lantern preparation. The festive atmosphere continues with community gatherings.</li>
        <li><strong>Day 15 &mdash; Lantern Festival (<span class="chinese-char">元宵節</span>)</strong> &mdash; The grand finale. Lanterns displayed, lantern riddles (<span class="chinese-char">燈謎</span>) solved. Families eat <em>tangyuan</em> (glutinous rice balls) symbolising togetherness. The first full moon of the new year.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="customs">
      <h2>Traditional Customs (Pre-Qing)</h2>
      <p><strong>Spring Couplets (<span class="chinese-char">春聯</span>)</strong> &mdash; Paired lines of auspicious poetry hung on doorframes. This literary tradition dates to the Five Dynasties period (907-960 CE), when they were carved on peach wood boards before evolving to red paper during the Ming Dynasty.</p>
      <p><strong>Door Gods (<span class="chinese-char">門神</span>)</strong> &mdash; Painted guardian figures on gates, a custom established by the Tang Dynasty. The most famous pair are Qin Shubao and Yuchi Gong, generals of Emperor Taizong.</p>
      <p><strong>Paper Cutting (<span class="chinese-char">剪紙</span>)</strong> &mdash; Intricate red paper designs depicting zodiac animals, flowers, and auspicious characters, displayed on windows to welcome the new year.</p>
      <p><strong>Red Envelopes (<span class="chinese-char">紅包</span>)</strong> &mdash; Containing lucky money (<span class="chinese-char">壓歲錢</span>, yāsuìqián, literally "money to suppress age"), given by elders to children as blessings for the coming year.</p>
      <p><strong>Firecrackers (<span class="chinese-char">鞭炮</span>)</strong> &mdash; Originally bamboo thrown into fires (which cracked loudly when heated), later evolving into gunpowder firecrackers after the Tang Dynasty invention of black powder.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="foods">
      <h2>Festival Foods</h2>
      <p><strong>Dumplings (<span class="chinese-char">餃子</span>)</strong> &mdash; Shaped like ancient gold ingots (<span class="chinese-char">元寶</span>), symbolising wealth. Families wrap them together on New Year's Eve. Dominant in northern China.</p>
      <p><strong>Nian Gao (<span class="chinese-char">年糕</span>)</strong> &mdash; Sticky rice cake. The name is a homophone for "year higher" (<span class="chinese-char">年高</span>), symbolising rising prosperity. Popular in southern and eastern China.</p>
      <p><strong>Fish (<span class="chinese-char">魚</span>)</strong> &mdash; Always served at the reunion dinner. <em>Yú</em> is a homophone of <span class="chinese-char">餘</span> (surplus), representing the wish for abundance.</p>
      <p><strong>Tang Yuan (<span class="chinese-char">湯圓</span>)</strong> &mdash; Glutinous rice balls eaten during the Lantern Festival. Their round shape symbolises family unity and completeness. The name evokes <span class="chinese-char">團圓</span> (tuányuán, reunion).</p>
    </section>

    <section id="kaigong-lishi">
      <h2>Kaigong Lishi — The Red Envelope's Song Dynasty Origin (<span class="chinese-char">開工利是</span>)</h2>
      <p>The modern practice of bosses distributing red envelopes to employees when businesses reopen after the New Year holiday (<span class="chinese-char">開工利是</span>, <span class="pinyin">Kāigōng Lìshì</span>) traces to a documented <strong>Southern Song Dynasty</strong> custom in the capital Lin'an (<span class="chinese-char">臨安</span>, modern Hangzhou).</p>
      <div class="source-box">
        <p>Zhou Mi (<span class="chinese-char">周密</span>, 1232–1298) recorded in <em>《武林舊事》</em> (<span class="pinyin">Wǔlín Jiùshì</span>, "Old Affairs of Wulin") that during the Lantern Festival season, government officials would distribute <strong><span class="chinese-char">楮券</span></strong> (<span class="pinyin">chǔquàn</span>, paper money / huizi) to small traders in a practice called <strong><span class="chinese-char">買市</span></strong> (<span class="pinyin">mǎishì</span>, "buying the market") — essentially stimulating commerce by giving merchants working capital.</p>
        <cite>— Zhou Mi, <em>《武林舊事》</em>, Southern Song Dynasty (c. 1270s)</cite>
      </div>
      <p>The term <strong><span class="chinese-char">利市</span></strong> (<span class="pinyin">lìshì</span>) itself is far older. It appears in the <em>《左氏傳》</em> (<span class="pinyin">Zuǒshì Zhuàn</span>, Zuo Commentary, Spring and Autumn period) and the <em>《易傳》</em> (<span class="pinyin">Yìzhuàn</span>, Commentary on the Book of Changes), where it means "profitable market" or "auspicious transaction." The Song Dynasty <strong><span class="chinese-char">利市袋兒</span></strong> (<span class="pinyin">lìshì dàir</span>, "lishi pouch") was a direct precursor of the modern red envelope.</p>
      <p>After the Song Dynasty, this specific custom of official money distribution appears to fade from historical records — it is not found in Ming or Qing sources in the same form. The modern revival of <span class="chinese-char">開工利是</span> occurs primarily in <strong>Guangdong, Hong Kong, Macau, and Taiwan</strong>, where the Cantonese pronunciation <strong>"利是" (lai see / lei si)</strong> preserves the ancient Chinese reading more closely than Mandarin "lìshì."</p>
    </section>

    <section id="performances">
      <h2>Temple Fairs and Performances</h2>
      <p>The <strong>lion dance</strong> and <strong>dragon dance</strong> date to the Han Dynasty. Temple fairs (<span class="chinese-char">廟會</span>) feature folk performances, stilt walking, <em>yangge</em> dancing, and opera. These gatherings served essential social functions in traditional Chinese society, reinforcing community bonds and providing entertainment during the long winter festival.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="lantern-festival">
      <h2>The Lantern Festival (<span class="chinese-char">元宵節</span>)</h2>
      <p>The Lantern Festival on the 15th day marks the first full moon of the new year. Tradition attributes its origins to Han Dynasty Emperor Ming, who ordered lanterns lit in palaces and temples to honour the Buddha. <strong>Lantern riddles</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">燈謎</span>) &mdash; riddles written on lanterns for people to solve &mdash; became a beloved intellectual pastime by the Song Dynasty.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="zodiac-connection">
      <h2>Spring Festival and the Zodiac</h2>
      <p>Each Chinese New Year ushers in a new <a href="/zodiac/">zodiac animal</a>. The incoming animal's personality is believed to colour the character of the entire year. People born in the same animal year enter their <strong>Ben Ming Nian</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">本命年</span>) &mdash; their own zodiac year &mdash; which is traditionally considered a year of challenges requiring special precautions, most notably wearing red undergarments throughout the year.</p>
    </section>
